Weekend reading: a classic on the importance of credible neutrality. Super excited that Farcaster is bringing this concept to life.

https://nakamoto.com/credible-neutrality/

Super cool, are there real-world examples of this?

Relevant to on-chain payments for services where customer's willingness to pay varies by token.

Example: DAOs need to pay for services but hold many tokens in their treasury. They may be more or less willing to pay with a given token depending on what else they use that token for (e.g. governance) and how much of it they hold.

Conversely, most Web2 co's only hold USD.

The DAOs I'm familiar with typically get a % share of protocol revenues, for example in the case of Aave. You can see the tokens in their treasury in this financial report:

https://llama.xyz/reports/aave/august-2022-financials.pdf

What I'm more focused on are how DAOs pay other service providers. In the case of Aave this is the "third party expenses" line item on page 12 of the report I shared. Unfortunately there isn't much detail given on the tokens used to make these payments.

That would be one potential implementation, yes. Inter-asset FX and liquidity risk would need to be addressed, however. The recipient would desire certainty & stability in the reference value of the index payment.
To that end, a few ideas on mechanisms for this to work at scale, using a $1.00 USD payment as an example:

1. Over-collateralization: payer pays $1.05 to compensate recipient for FX and liquidity risk.

2. Smart contract insurance: payer or insurance entity re-collateralizes the payment if realized value falls below $1.00.
3. Instant swap: Index payment automatically routes through a DEX and is converted to $1.00 in the same block.

I would imagine so, right? What if the index payment is made for $1, and the next day it's worth $0.90? The recipient of an index payment (or any floating currency payment, frankly) would probably want to lock in the payment value as soon as possible after receiving the payment.

It's a super interesting topic! I'm optimistic there could be ways to incentivize holding, rather than liquidation to USD upon receipt. Beside the recipient, liquidation would be undesirable for the payer, as it could add to sell-pressure on their DAO's native token for example.

One thing to think through is how token mechanisms beyond use as currency could incentivize holding in index wallets. Examples: tokens received as payment could have some claim to the payer protocol's staking rewards, revenue share, or governance rights.

Thoughts on the NFT royalties debate: Marketplaces of all types must compete on fulfillment of end user demands, or risk market share loss. It creates a race to the bottom. 🧵

The royalty issue thus won't be solved at the marketplace level. Moreover, if no marketplaces fulfill demand for a feature, a fork will. Proliferation of forked NFT marketplaces and DEXs demonstrates this.

As such, creators should think about how to:
- (1) make royalties technically enforceable or structural to the project.
- (2) incentivize users to pay royalties.

Projects shouldn't fault end users for wanting to pay less, even if they support a community.

Prediction: the projects that address this issue head-on will survive and thrive, and come out of the bear market even stronger.
